article.headline: Holdsclaw helps send Shock to 0-10
article.linkText: Mystics stay hot while Shock's deep freeze continues
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw scored 24 points and
combined with Stacey Dales-Schuman to spark a late run that helped
the Washington Mystics keep the Detroit Shock winless this season
with a 75-67 victory Tuesday night.

	   The Mystics won their sixth straight and improved to a
franchise-best 7-1 by finishing the game with a 13-3 run.

	   "I'm happy that we found out that we can win ugly,'' Washington
coach Marianne Stanley said. "We battled at critical moments down
the stretch. It was just a gutty team effort.''

	   Washington led most of the game until Wendy Palmer scored seven
of her 16 points in a nine-point run that gave the Shock (0-10) a
46-40 lead with just under 14 minutes left.

	   Detroit held the lead for several minutes before Holdsclaw and
Dales-Schuman combined on their late-game streak. Each scored five
points -- and those were Dales-Schuman's only ones of the game.

	   Holdsclaw, who had 11 rebounds for her fifth double-double, gave
the Mystics the lead for good at 65-64 on a three-point play with
4:26 left. She then stretched the lead to 67-64 with a bank shot at
3:02.

	   "It's different when you're being the hunted,'' Holdsclaw said.
"Everyone is going to come out and give you their best shot. We're
just going to have to be sharp.''

	   Dales-Schuman then scored four straight points as Washington
took a 71-64 lead with 1:28 left. The Shock had only two field
goals over the final five minutes.

	   Foul trouble plagued the Mystics throughout the second half.
With 15 minutes left, Washington had four starters with three
fouls, including Holdsclaw.

	   The Mystics shot just 40 percent in the first half -- well below
their league-leading 49 percent -- but still led 32-28 at halftime.

	   Washington guard Coco Miller scored eight of her career-high 15
points in the second half and rookie reserve Asjha Jones added 10
points for the Mystics.

	   Deanna Nolan also had 16 points for the Shock.

	   Detroit returns for a home game after playing eight of its first
10 on the road.

	   "We've been on the road 19 of the last 22 days,'' Shock coach
Greg Williams said. "They're a very good basketball team.''
